Edward,<br>
Yes, the draft did focus on those who did not have the means to escape with a deferment.  But, bear in mind that the poorest population is smoetimes excused, rightfuuly so with a hardship deferment.  Instead the draft focused on the blue collar lower middle class and working class neighborhoods, followed then with poorer populations.  Take a look at New York City, many middle class, blue collar neighborhoods had very high rates of service and mortality in Vietnam.  The middle class part of the city where my father lived had 80 men die in Vietnam and countless others serve.<br>
Likewise, Dept of Veterans Affairs, Dept of Defense and Dept of Labor Statistics report that 76% of men sent to Vietnam were from lower middle class/working class backgrounds.  Three-fourths had family income levels above the poverty line, with 50% from middle class backgrounds.  23% of all Nam vets had fathers with professional, managerial or technical occupations.  So, Vietnam vets were not necessarily the poor of America.  By saying that it demeans both the poor that served and the blue collar, middle class men who served there country.<br>
In addition only 25% of total forces in country were draftees, while 70% were volunteers (some volunteered because they were about to be drafted).  <br><br>
Education levels-Dept of Defense and Dept of Veterans Affairs reports that 79% of those who served in Vietnam had a high school education or better when they entered military service. (I am a school teacher and the high school completion rate of today is 85%)  Compare this to my World War II, where 28% of American forces were high school dropouts, 33% had only completed Elementary schhol, and only 14% of those in uniform had attended collge (3% were college graduates).  World War II soldiers (due in large part to the demands of working to support their families during the depression) had lower education levels, but served proudly and used the GI Bill after World War II to continue schooling.<br><br>
I do agree whole hearted that many people hid behind a college deferment, or make believe set of ailments.  A good example is a well written about draft physical in Boston, where most of the College men from the big schhols in Boston were defered with a host of deferments and physical ailments, and most of the blue collar kids were stamped 1-A for military service.  No America was not fair and the draft is CERTAINLY NOT FAIR.  I would no support another draft that allows tons of deferments, and the excusal of men based on the word of some high priced private doctor.<br><br>
Also, I think no one knem what they were getting into!!  Do you Veterans agree?<br><br>
I disagree with you though.  First of all Nam vets are not malingers, if they need help they deserve it.  If any man can get any money out of the VA, then they should try.  Is it OK for this country to take young men, sent them off to a far away horrible war, then when they come home forget them and any problems they have?  NO it is not OK.  If Vietnam vets still seeks VA help they deserve, well they are entitled to it.  This country helped the World War II vet out totally, but ignored the Vietnam Vet.  So, if Nam vets are still seeking help for injuries, PTSD or Agent Orange, I support them the whole way.  America spent 400 billion dollars on the War, yet it took wounded vets months or years to get treatment they deserved.  The VA owes eveyone an explanation!!  I don't know about you, but most Nam Vets are proud at least about some part of there service.  A Official Poll of Nam vets found that 91% of Vietnam vets and 90% of those who saw heavy combat say they are proud to serve.  Say what you want about this poll (everyone has things they are not proud of), but I believe to be true.  Vietnam vets are now coming to grips with their service, seeking out old buddies in great numbers and discovering things about themselves.  I think it is a good time for the Nam vet, or at least the best since the end of the war.<br><br>
The Vietnam vet was not the poor uneducated kid for the most part back then, and now he is a big part of our society today.  The Vietnam war will never end, it just can't.<br><br>
Anyway, Peace to all Nam vets and keep your ammo dry!!
